data.reasoningText:
The issue is that the global.json doesn't pin an SDK version, so it's using the latest installed SDK (11.0.100-preview.3). But the baseline ran with `dotnet test` and succeeded. Let me check - maybe the global.json somehow controlled which SDK was used.

Wait, the global.json only has:
```json
{
  "test": {
    "runner": "VSTest"
  }
}
```

It doesn't have an `sdk` section. So the latest SDK (11.0.100-preview.3) is used. But `net8.0-windows` requires the Windows Desktop targeting pack, which isn't available on Linux.


The baseline test passed, so the build must have worked then. I'm wondering if there's a difference in how the global.json is configured now, or if there's a roll-forward happening. Maybe the `xunit.v3` package is pulling in a dependency that conflicts with the `net8.0-windows` target framework.

The real issue seems to be that `Microsoft.WindowsDesktop.App` isn't recognized when using the .NET 11 SDK on Linux, but the .NET 8 SDK might handle this differently—perhaps with a warning instead of an error. The `net8.0-windows` TFM with the older xunit v2 packages worked fine because those packages didn't explicitly reference `Microsoft.WindowsDesktop.App`. Let me try pinning the SDK version in global.json to force the .NET 8 SDK.

